Current State

  - All user-submitted .py files go through the pyda path (DParser AST)
  - __pyc__.py (the builtin module, 539 lines) still uses the CPython path because DParser is too slow
  on it
  - The guard in pyc.cc: m->pymod = m->is_builtin ? nullptr : dparse_python_to_ast(filename)

  Next Phases

  Phase 6: Fix DParser Performance on __pyc__.py

  The 45,257-state grammar causes super-linear GLR complexity on larger files. Options:
  - Profile what's causing slowness (ambiguity in grammar rules?)
  - Reduce state count by simplifying/disambiguating grammar rules
  - Once fast enough, remove the is_builtin guard so __pyc__.py also goes through pyda

  Phase 7: Remove the CPython AST Path

  Once __pyc__.py goes through pyda:
  - Remove the CPython build_syms(mod_ty) / build_if1(stmt_ty/expr_ty) codepaths
  - Remove CPython parser dependency (Python-2.7.18/ bundled copy)
  - This is the major payoff — the codebase becomes much simpler

  Phase 8: Extend Language Coverage

  Fill in any Python 2.7 features not yet handled in the pyda path (e.g., exec, with, generator
  expressions as standalone statements, etc.)

  ---
  The most impactful next step is Phase 6 — profiling and fixing DParser's slowness on __pyc__.py.
  Would you like to start there? I can profile it with callgrind or add timing instrumentation to
  identify the bottleneck.



